There’s something real in that—but it’s not just “removing filters.”

When you get sleepy, the brain shifts modes:

* Top-down control drops (the “editor”/filtering system—mainly frontal cortex—gets quieter)
* Bottom-up signals and associations loosen (sensory + memory fragments mix more freely)

That can show up in two ways:

1) Not hallucinating—just less filtered

* thoughts feel more fluid, less censored
* unusual connections come easier
* attention drifts, boundaries blur

This is what you’re describing as “filters coming off.”

